[1]
Date: Fri, 11 Nov 2005
From: Rob Fergus <rfergus@audubon.org>
Source: CTV.CA, 11 Nov 2005 [edited]
<http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20051111/kuwait_bird_flu_051111/20051111?hub=3DTopStories>

One of 2 birds found infected with bird flu in Kuwait has the deadly
H5N1 strain of the virus, health authorities have confirmed. H5N1 is
the strain that has devastated poultry stocks and killed more than 60
people in Asia.
The infected bird was a migrating flamingo found on a Kuwait beach.
The other was an imported falcon found to have the milder H5N2
variant.
The infected birds in Kuwait are the 1st known cases of the virus in
the Persian Gulf region.
A senior official said the government didn't plan to cull any birds
following the confirmation.
"Immediate action was taken ... and the situation is under control,"
said Sheik Fahd Salem Al Ali Al Sabah, chairman of the Public
Authority for Agriculture and Fisheries.
Last month, Kuwait said it had earmarked USD 17 million to buy drugs
to combat bird flu.
The entire Middle East region has been worried about possible
outbreaks because the region sits on important migratory bird
waterways south. Jordan and Israel have been among the other
countries trying to impose precautions to prevent outbreaks.
--
Rob Fergus
Science Coordinator
National Audubon Science Office
545 Almshouse Road, Ivyland PA 18974-1119
<rfergus@audubon.org>
[The affected bird is, most probably, a Greater Flamingo,
_Phoenicopterus roseus_. This species, the only flamingo recorded in
Kuwait (See Avibase, the world bird database
<http://www.bsc-eoc.org/avibase/avibase.jsphas>), has the most
widespread distribution of all flamingo species. Populations are
found in northwest India, the Middle East, the western Mediterranean
and Africa. Limited numbers can be found over much of northern
Europe, eastward to Siberia. Though generally regarded as
non-migratory, populations that breed in lakes that may freeze over
in the winter, move to warmer areas, and return in springtime. When
flamingos migrate, they do so mainly at night and can travel
approximately 600 km (373 miles) in one night at about 50 to 60 kph
(31-37 mph).
Greater flamingos were among the birds clinically affected by H5N1 in
the Penfold Park, Hong Kong SAR, in November 2002.
Information from knowledgeable sources about migration patterns and
origin(s) of flamingos visiting the Middle and Near East,
particularly the gulf area, will be gratefully received. - Mod.AS]
