[2]
Date: Fri, 11 Nov 2005
From: Jim Kent <jim.kent@virgin.net>

Re your requests for information about possible transport of H5N1 by
migratory birds, your readers are referred to the BBC nature
programme from Slimbridge (Wildfowl and Wetlands Trust Centre near
Gloucester, UK) which earlier this week held a discussion devoted to
bird flu and wild bird involvement.
During the programme, Prof. Chris Feare pointed out that although
H5N1 outbreaks in Siberia followed migratory bird routes, they were
also close to the Trans-Siberian railway and road corridor and
occurred in summer when birds were moulting and non-migratory,
suggesting human involvement in virus transport.
Programme can be heard again via website:
<http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/science/nature.shtml>.
Part 2 of 2-part BBC Panorama investigation into bird flu is to be
broadcast next Sunday [13 Nov 2005] and again, there should be video
feed available on the BBC website.
--
Jim Kent
Emergency Planning Officer (Retired)
Somerset, UK
<jim.kent@virgin.net>
