[3]
Date: Fri, 11 Nov 2005
From: Nati Elkin <nati@poultrymed.com>
Source: AGI online, 11 Nov 2005 [edited]
<http://www.agi.it/english/news.pl?doc=200511101740-0182-RT1-CRO-0-NF11&page=0&id=agionline-eng.oggitalia>

The wild duck that was positive for H5N1 (but at low pathogenicity,
not dangerous to human health) was a mallard killed by a hunter in
the Modena province 20 days ago. Mauro Delogu, a researcher at
Bologna University, said that they had already cooked it.
Delogu has activated a monitoring network on migratory bird viruses
in Italy and has discovered the 1st case of bird flu in Italy. "The
laboratory of Bologna University made the first tests on the samples
collected among wild fauna in several towns in Italy. When we
registered this 1st suspect case we sent it to the reference centre
in Legnaro (Padua) to identify the virus," he said. The virus was
found in a young male of mallard aged around 1 year, which was killed
by a hunter in Modena province. Delogu said that probably the bird
was not migratory. It was probably born in Italy, due to its young
age. The virus could be also of local origin too.
The tests run in Padua confirmed that it was a low pathogenicity
virus that is [substantially different from] the Asian virus.
"Speaking about the virus as being H5N1 means speaking about a virus
[within a group] that has many differences," the researcher said.
This is the 1st time in 13 years that an Italian researcher has found
an H5N1 virus in Italian wild birds. The discovery is good news,
because the virus has a low pathogenicity and can boost the immune
system of the birds, helping them to resist the Asian strain. "Nature
develops its defences in a marvellous way" he said.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The above information, if accurate, provides the information
requested in 20051110.3286: species (mallard, _Anas platyrhynchos_),
location (Modena, see map at
<http://www.fallingrain.com/world/IT/5/Modena.html>), origin
(probably local) and clinical status (probably non-clinical, hunted
young male).
It will help if data on the methods applied to identify the virus and
determine the (allegedly low) pathogenicity of the involved H5N1
virus strain, are made available.
Surveillance in wild birds has recently become a European Union
priority and guidelines made available (see 20051027.3134). The
guidelines include a provisional list of (15) wild bird species
presenting higher risk in relation to avian influenza. Mallards are
included. - Mod.AS]
